This article is a transcript of a conversation between President Donald Trump and American astronauts Peggy Whitson, Jack Fischer, and Kate Rubins who are aboard the International Space Station. The President congratulates Commander Whitson on breaking the record for the most time spent in space by an American astronaut. They discuss the importance of space research and the need for international cooperation in future missions to Mars. The astronauts also talk about their daily activities in space and the advancements in technology that allow them to conduct experiments and research. President Trump emphasizes the opportunities for young students to get involved in space exploration and the military applications of space technology. He expresses his commitment to sending American astronauts to Mars and encourages students to study math, science, and engineering to be a part of future space missions. The President praises the astronauts for their bravery and contributions to space exploration.